It turns out @AmanaCare was not particularly helpful, they asked if I had an extended warranty after already determining that the device was 10 yrs old (ex. warr. only goes 1/2/5 yrs)...

1/N

From search-fu determined that it was likely the control board went out. 😢

Of course ... Amazon has them...

2/N

Ordered the control board from Amazon... took a week to arrive (1st clue). Spent ... too long ... trying to get the unit into "program mode" (2nd clue).

3/N

Determined (guessed) due to above that the Amazon device was probably damaged similar to mine and not a new board 😢

4/N

Called local repairman. They were two weeks out! But suggested I book the appt., order a new part ,and try it myself and if my installation failed then use the appt.... 

5/N

New part arrives! (Have to return my old part as a "core" part (hence belief that amazon part was defective))... And it works! 🎉
1st world living!

6/N

Takeaways: 

✅Just because it is on Amazon doesn't mean it is new/works. 
✅Support local biz (part was cheaper there anyway)
✅$160 part took 5 minutes to install vs $3000 new refrigerator

END!

Using inplace=True violates one of my Pandas rules: do not use inplace=True

Why not?

🙍 It makes it hard to chain operations
🙍 It makes it hard to read code
🙍 Most inplace operations are not "inplace"
🙍 It will probably be deprecated

Always use the named parameter "columns" and don't use inplace=True: https://t.co/hcFJX12jGA

You can use this pattern of taking the mean of a series with boolean values to calculate the percentage of arbitrary information.

The percent of entries equal to 21–29: https://t.co/fYCWAYXsfK
My final code would leverage an f-string to format the number: https://t.co/ONrJ1sOK9L

We could divide this by the length to get our answer, but with a little creativity, it is even easier.

If you have a sequence of 0s and 1s (trues and falses 😉), we can take the average value to calculate the fraction of 1s (or trues): https://t.co/J0ozUet6Sl
It turns out that Python treats True as 1 and False as 0. (This is because Python didn't have booleans until version 2.0, so devs frequently treated 1 as true). https://t.co/ArgMHHDZGD
We can leverage this fact to easily count the number of missing values in a pandas series by summing it: https://t.co/Xm16Cs1fpy

🤔 Uses numpy to round

Tuples can be used for:

🐍 Record-type data
🐍 Returning multiple items from a function
🐍 *Unpacking* in assignment or for loops
🐍 Hashing sequences
🐍 Slots

First of all ... pronunciation.

You can say "two-pull" or "tuh-pull" (both are valid).

A big confusion is when to use a list or tuple?

My basic rule of thumb:

If you have items of the same type and care about the order or re-arranging it, you want a list.
If you have a sequence of items with different types (then you wouldn't be re-arranging it), and the order is important, then tuple.

I'm teaching a Fundamentals of Python class this week.

We talked about tuples, and there was some confusion as to their existence.

Certainly, you could live in a world without them, but...

🧵
Some examples from the standard library: https://t.co/mRXOaJr5hS
You can create them with a literal or the constructor. (There is also the unpack operator, but I find this hard to grok). https://t.co/YIJp2bPs2I

One annoying thing with pulling things out of tuples, is that you often introduce "magic numbers". If that is a problem, consider a named tuple (there are 2 ways to create them): https://t.co/qp9ImhhS9Q

Thanks for reading 🙏

@cbrnr_ Yes, the order. Items in a tuple have a specific order, and if you break that contract things go south.

Lists have an order, but that can change (and is often expected to).
@cbrnr_ Often you do "mapping" operations on items in a list. So they should be the same (duck) type.

My experience has led me to believe that job seeking is a skill. Like any skill, you can learn it and grow it. Here are five tips to improving your job situation:

Getting a Tech Job 101

With the allure of FAANG and human nature's tendency for comparison, job seeking can be depressing.

However, this skill is more important than ever.

A thread 🧵 https://t.co/o6bIwPhTP5

You want to be moving up and to the right. However, if you are just getting started in your career, the lower left might work. https://t.co/RJdfsvQZg5

2/ Evaluate your skills gap.

Given the skills required for your new job, you need to determine where to level up. Ask others, do the work, make sure you are qualified.

What are your job search tips? 🤔

Please share with this with your network who may be looking to better their own situation 🙏

I asked my network for their tips...

Truth is most people get their job from their network. If you don't invest in this, you are paddling upstream. https://t.co/n7h4dthFBz

As much as you might think you are in a meritocracy, often those with better people skills will jump the line.

These are also "skills" that you can learn with practice.

As you work on them, you will improve. https://t.co/BiUrPwB8eZ

If you can master these tips, your job search will be much smoother.

Once you have new skills, you need be able to demonstrate them. What does your portfolio look like?

The bare minimum is listing a skill on your resume. https://t.co/GhHi8LkjF9

One of my favorite courses to teach is Intermediate Python.

We dive into functions so we can understand (sometimes brain-bending) concepts like decorators and closures.

This thread will explore positional-only and keyword-only arguments for functions (and methods).

🤯🐍

Why are these important?

- If you read documentation (which you should), you will run across them
- They can make your code better
- Knowledge is power

Let's start off with an example. The "sorted" built-in function, has both positional-only and keyword-only parameters. If you've looked at the documentation for it, you may have wondered what the "/" and "*" mean. https://t.co/nPrUpD5Zkv

The "/" in the function declaration is a positional only marker (PEP 570, Python 3.8+).

If we try and sort a sequence, we cannot use the "iterable" name with it. If we do, we get a "TypeError" (with a somewhat cryptic message): https://t.co/Dh4Q9MfqID

Why was this syntax added?

- Many CPython built-ins have this behavior since Python 1.0
- Some functions have arguments that have a natural order.
- "dict" supports this so you can pass in a mapping, or use named parameters to create dictionaries

When to use positional-only arguments?

If your code requires natural ordering of parameters (very rare), you are implementing CPython code (rare), you want to create fancy dict-like behavior (rare).

Personally, I've never used them in my own code.
On to keyword-only arguments. Python 3.0 introduced this feature (PEP 3102). Any parameter following a bare "*" must also provide the argument name.

When to use keyword-only arguments? My take is that almost all arguments could benefit from the additional context provided by a keyword.

This will often cleanup "magic numbers". Compare: https://t.co/1V1Q2ntflT
Here's an example with sorted. We need to provide "key=" if we pass in a key function. Again, the error message if you violate this contract could be clearer: https://t.co/ER7tefVcTA
To force this behavior change the function to: https://t.co/iNFn9c1PZ9

Thanks for exploring functions with me. If you enjoyed this thread, please share it and follow me for more Python content.

This is called "rubber duck" debugging because people will speak to an inanimate object to get advice. The important part is to say it OUT LOUD (From "The Pragmatic Programmer")

🙏 Thanks for reading!

What is your favorite advice for debugging?

Follow me for more programming-related tips.

Simplify/Test - "It works for me" is frustrating. You need to come up with the most simple version of the problem sometimes to get help. Writing tests can aid in this (and protect from future problems).
Debugger - A tool that allows for breakpoints and inspecting code can be useful. However, I find that the above steps often work before that.

Sleep on it - Another brain hack is called "incubation".  I've slept on problems multiple times and woken up knowing what to do. Your brain will churn on issues even when you step away.

This is why pulling all-nighters trying to fix things is a misguided approach.
Print debugging - I use this all the time. Programming genius I know also use it. You can bend this into logging for production debugging.
Rubber duck - It turns out that you use a different portion of your brain when you vocalize your problems. Often times in the middle of describing it, you know your misstep.

Here are my debugging tips:

💪 Prepare
💪 Use "print" debugging
💪 Rubber duck it 🦆
💪 Sleep on it
💪 Debugger
💪 Simplify/Test
At some point, we will need to start debugging. This is a skill that young kids can master. (My daughter typoed some code last night and was able to fix it)

When I teach programming, I emphasize that to me, the most important part is that the code is "readable."

You write code (once or twice), but it is read all the time. Optimize for what happens a lot.

Not:

😦 Brevity
😦 Cleverness
😦 Using all of the features

Debugging is twice as hard as writing the code in the first place. Therefore, if you write the code as cleverly as possible, you are, by definition, not smart enough to debug it.

-Kernighan's Law

🤯

Some history. Python didn't include booleans, so folks did:

   >>> true = 1
   >>> false = 0

And went about their lives. When booleans were added to the language, backwards compatibility was maintained for these folks. So you can do this:

    >>> True + 41
    42 https://t.co/KVw6Sqe3Nn

More factoids:

"Truthiness" is determined by the .__bool__ method. Most empty, zero, or None objects evaluate to false in a boolean context:

>>> bool('')
False

>>> bool(0)
False

>>> bool([])
False

Big O notation (pronounced Big-Oh) is a way to discuss how long an algorithm takes to run. It is also called "runtime complexity".

Understanding this is key for technologists.

Let's look at it.

1/

If we want to calculate the mean of a sequence, a naive implementation will calculate the sum and divide it by the length:

2/ https://t.co/018pkdM8pi

Often we express Big O in terms of the size of the data and N is commonly used to represent the numbers of items.

We have to loop over every item in seq. There are N items, so the runtime complexity of the mean function is O(N).

3/

If there are 1 million items, we have to loop over 1 million items. So we express it in terms of N.

4/

On average, sorted_search only looks at 19 items for lists of size 1,000,000.

This function is O(logN). It only looks at the log of the number of items.

7/

However, we can take advantage of the order and find items quicker. A binary search does not look at each item but finds a central point, and if the item is less than the center, it only considers the half of the items. It repeats this process.

6/ https://t.co/X8G4o5BSbe

If we have a sorted list and want to search for an item, we could loop through the list until we find the item.

This code is considered O(N) because it is looping over the list (even if it finds the value in index position 0).

5/ https://t.co/evVjo6xdOB

Thanks for reading. 👏

What code do I prefer? I try to focus on making readable code. While I understand comprehensions, I don't favor complex comprehensions and I would probably write out the for loop. Just because you can write less lines of code doesn't mean that you always should.
